##Angular Client Auth Consumer Documentation

###Resources:
* [Yeoman : Getting Started](http://yeoman.io/learning/index.html)
* [Yeoman : FAQ](http://yeoman.io/learning/faq.html)
* [Yeoman : Resources Page](http://yeoman.io/learning/resources.html)
* [Yeoman : Angular Generator](https://github.com/yeoman/generator-angular)
* [ngStorage : GitHub Repo](https://github.com/gsklee/ngStorage)

###Instructions
1. Scaffold Angular Base App

    1. Make a new directory to contain the decoupled front-end code (which should be inside the project root folder)

        ```shell
        mkdir sample-client && cd $_
        ```

    2. Run Yeoman Angular Scaffolding procedure

        ```shell
        yo angular authSampleApp
        ```

        For the purposes of this demonstration, you do not require Sass with compass. (Press `n`)

        Include Bootstrap in this project. (Press `Y`)

        Include all preseleted modules. (Press `Enter`)

        ```shell
        [?] Would you like to use Sass (with Compass)? (Y/n) No
        [?] Would you like to include Bootstrap? (Y/n) Yes
        [?] Which modules would you like to include? (Press <space> to select)
         [X] angular-animate.js
         [X] angular-cookies.js
         [X] angular-resource.js
         [X] angular-route.js
         [X] angular-sanitize.js
         [X] angular-touch.js
        ```

    3. Test Launch Base App Server

        ```shell
        grunt serve
        ```
2. Install ngStorage Dependency

    1. Install bower component ngStorage

        ```shell
        bower install ngstorage --save
        ```

    2. Wire up dependencies
        ```shell
        grunt wiredep
        ```

    3. Register Angular dependency in ~app/scripts/app.js
       ```shell
       vim app/scripts/app.js
       ```

       Add `ngStorage` to the list of dependencies as below:
       ```
       'ngSanitize',
       'ngTouch',
       'ngStorage'
       ```

3. Generate Login Route

    1. Create Login Route

        ```shell
        yo angular:route login
        ```

4. Modify Login View

    1. Create and edit ~views/login.html
        ```shell
        vim app/views/login.html
        ```

    2. Add the following content:

        ```html
        <section class="content">
            <form id="login-form" ng-submit="authenticate()" >
                <img class="logo" src="data:image/png;base64,">

                <input id="username" class="form-control" type="text" placeholder="Username" ng-model="credentials.username">
                <input id="password" class="form-control" type="password" placeholder="Password" ng-model="credentials.password">

                <button class="btn btn-info pull-right" type="button" ng-click="checkEmail()">Check Email</button>
                <button class="btn btn-default pull-right">Login</button>

            </form>
        </section>
        ```


5. Modify Login Controller

    1. Edit ~controllers/login.js
        ```shell
        vim app/scripts/controllers/login.js
        ```

    2. Find and replace where appropriate with the following content:

        ```js
        .controller('LoginCtrl', function ($scope, $http, $localStorage) {
           var AUTH_URL = '<auth server url>',
               CLIENT_ID = '<received client id>';

           // Initialize Credentials
           $scope.credentials = {
               username: '',
               password: ''
           };

           /**
            * This function pulls the username and passwords from login page
            * and POST's via AJAX to the OAuth server.
            * If the credentials are valid it will call the loginSuccess function.
            * Otherwise if the credentials are not valid it will call the loginError function.
            * @function authenticate
            */
           $scope.authenticate = function () {
               var url = AUTH_URL + '/oauth/token',
                   data = {
                       grant_type: 'password',
                       client_id: CLIENT_ID,
                       username: $scope.credentials.username,
                       password: $scope.credentials.password
                   };

               //Clear away previous token
               delete $localStorage.token;

               $http.post(url, data)
                   .success($scope.authenticateSuccess)
                   .error($scope.authenticateError);
           };


           /**
            * @function authenticateSuccess
            */
           $scope.authenticateSuccess = function (data) {
               $localStorage.token = data.access_token;
               console.log('Logged in');
               alert('Logged in! \n\n Now check email!');
           };

           /**
            * @function authenticateError
            */
           $scope.authenticateError = function () {
               // Handle login errors here
               console.log('Login fail');
               alert('Invalid username or password');
           };

           /**
            * @function checkEmail
            */
           $scope.checkEmail = function () {
               var url = AUTH_URL + '/oauth/token-info';

               $http.get(url)
                   .success($scope.checkEmailSuccess)
                   .error($scope.checkEmailError);
           };

           /**
            * @function checkEmailSuccess
            */
           $scope.checkEmailSuccess = function (data) {
               console.log("Check Email Succeeded!");
               alert('Email is: ' + data.identity.email);
           };

           /**
            * @function checkEmailError
            */
           $scope.checkEmailError = function () {
               console.log("Check Email Failed!")
           };

       });
        ```

    3. Update Auth Configuration

       A `CLIENT ID` should be app unique and can be obtained by registering a new client. [See OAuth Tutorial](OAUTH_README.md#section-b-advanced-test)

       At the top of the controller file, update the `AUTH_URL` and `CLIENT_ID` variables to the correct values.

       ```js
       var AUTH_URL = '<auth server url>',
           CLIENT_ID = '<received client id><received client id>';
       ```


6. Generate Auth Interceptor Factory

    1. Generate the factory with yeoman:

        ```shell
        yo angular:factory authInterceptor
        ```

    1. Edit the file:
    
        ```sh
        vim app/scripts/services/authinterceptor.js
        ```
        
    2. Find and add where appropriate the following content:

        ```js
        .factory('authInterceptor', function ($q, $localStorage) {
               return {
                   request: function (config) {
                       config.headers = config.headers || {};
                       if ($localStorage.token) {
                           config.headers.Authorization = 'Bearer ' +  $localStorage.token;
                       }
                       return config || $q.when(config);
                   },

                   requestError: function(error){
                       alert('Error processing request!')
                       return $q.reject(error);
                   },


                   response: function (response) {
                       //Possibly modify responses
                       return response || $q.when(response);;
                   },


                   responseError: function(error){
                       if (error.status == 401) {
                           alert('Request is unauthorized!');
                       }

                       //Handle other common errors

                       return $q.reject(error);
                   }
               };
           }) // End of factory

           .config(function ($httpProvider) {
               $httpProvider.interceptors.push('authInterceptor');
           });
        ```


7. Update Main Template (Navigation and Miscellaneous Updates)

    1. Edit ~index.html

        ```shell
        vim app/index.html
        ```

    2. Add the following list item to the navigation:
        ```html
        <li><a ng-href="#/login">Login</a></li>
        ```

8. Update Styling

    1. Edit ~/app/styles/main.css

        ```shell
        vim app/styles/main.css
        ```

    2. Insert the following code on ~line 81:

        ```css
        .content{
            padding-top: 30px;
            min-height: 580px;
        }

        #login-form{
            margin: 0 auto;
            max-width: 250px;
        }

        #login-form .logo{
            display:block;
            margin: 0 auto;
            width: 100%;
            max-width: 200px;
        }

        #login-form input {
            display: block;
            margin: 4px auto;
        }

        #login-form button{
            margin: 4px 0 0 4px;
        }


        ```

9.  Test login page.
    1. Launch your project with Grunt:

        ```shell
            grunt serve
        ```
        Your browser should open up to `http://localhost:9000/#/`

        Also, it is assumed that the OAuth server is running at the URL at Step 7.3


    2. Navigate to the login page by clicking `Login` in the top right corner.

       You should see:
           * an Awesomesauce logo
           * Username and Password fields
           * Login and Check Email buttons

    3. First, attempt to login without entering any credentials.

       (Assuming your session storage is cleared)

       You should receive an error:
       ```
       Invalid username or password
       ```

    4. Next, try to check email without logging in.

       You should receive and error
       ```
       Request is unauthorized!
       ```

    5. Assuming you have already have a registered user account, enter your credentials.

       You should receive a message:
       ```
       Logged in!

       Now check email!
       ```

    6. Now click on the `Check Email` button.

       You should receive a message:
       ```
       Email is: <your-email-here>
       ```
       with the user's email address in the message
